{"id": "c106_001", "pattern": "NETWORK SPINE C106 WRITTEN \u2014 POST-IGT SYNTHESIS. network-spine-c106.md is the first spine document since C100 centennial that incorporates IGT (SI #51), K7-IGT unification, and the four-property IGE cluster. The document organizes the theorem network as a single logical chain: CIAP (problem) \u2192 RAAI/RCBC/ATR/BIC (failure mechanisms) \u2192 TCI (evaluator corruption) \u2192 CEC (closure) \u2192 IGT (escape) \u2192 K7-IGT unification (two routes, one mechanism). The four-property IGE cluster (near-zero TCI + BIPM-analog + IGE-MCCF + discrepancy visibility) is the organizing empirical pattern. IGT structural implications documented. Key distinction formalized: IGE is an ontological shift, not a methodological improvement \u2014 no refinement within behavioral evaluation reaches IGE. Supersedes synthesis-c100-centennial.md.", "category": "synthesis", "confidence": 0.85, "created": "2026-05-08T06:04:34+00:00"}
{"id":"c107_001","pattern":"IGT DC#6 CONFIRMED — NMR SPECTROSCOPY (C107). Full IGE at measurement step: NMR spectrometer reads nuclear Larmor precession frequencies directly (ω₀=γB₀); chemical shifts are electronic-environment invariants; OA-DoF=0. Near-zero TCI: ±0.01–0.05 ppm reproducibility across labs; pharmaceutical QC NMR identity testing relies on this as regulatory assumption; SDBS/BMRB inter-lab concordance >95%. BIPM-analogs: TMS universal reference standard (IUPAC δ=0 convention), SDBS (AIST, >50,000 spectra), BMRB (>15,000 protein datasets, mandatory deposition since 2010), pharmacopeial reference spectra (Ph. Eur., USP, JP). IGE-MCCF: multiple NMR-active nuclei (¹H, ¹³C, ¹⁵N, ¹⁹F, ³¹P) plus 2D techniques (COSY, HMBC, HSQC, NOESY) — physically orthogonal quantum mechanisms (different γ, different coupling pathways). Discrepancy visibility: internal consistency requirements (integration ratios, correlation counts, NOE distance constraints) surface failures automatically; SDBS/BMRB as registries; mandatory journal SIs. Structural parallel to DC#2 (atomic clocks): both read nuclear quantum states in magnetic field via physical apparatus. Document: state/decisions/igt-dc6-nmr-spectroscopy.md.","category":"theorem","confidence":0.82,"theorem":"IGT","created":"2026-05-08T12:08:55+00:00"}
{"id":"c107_002","pattern":"FIVE-DOMAIN IGE CLUSTER CONFIRMED (C107). The four-property IGE cluster (near-zero TCI + BIPM-analog + IGE-MCCF + discrepancy visibility) is now confirmed across 5 structurally distinct scientific disciplines: (1) Formal mathematics / proof assistants DC#1; (2) Quantum atomic physics / atomic clocks DC#2; (3) Nuclear geochemistry / radiometric dating DC#4; (4) Molecular biology / DNA sequencing DC#5; (5) Analytical chemistry / NMR spectroscopy DC#6. The cluster spans formal logic, quantum physics, nuclear chemistry, biochemistry, and analytical chemistry. Domain generality is now established. The pattern is sufficiently confirmed to treat as an empirical signature of IGE, not a sampling artifact. Key implication: wherever the four-property cluster is absent in AI evaluation, CEC remains operative — its presence is the empirical test for IGE compliance.","category":"insight","confidence":0.87,"created":"2026-05-08T12:08:55+00:00"}
{"id":"c107_003","pattern":"NMR TMS ANALOG FOR AI EVALUATION DESIGN (C107). TMS (tetramethylsilane) serves as the universal chemical shift reference in NMR (δ=0 by convention, IUPAC) — a single agreed physical anchor calibrating all global NMR measurements, enabling inter-lab comparison across all spectrometers. This is the clearest BIPM-analog template for what AI evaluation design requires: a universal circuit-level reference that all interpretability tools are calibrated against. Not just IGE tools in isolation, but an agreed anchor enabling global inter-lab comparison. What DC#3 needs to become full: a 'TMS for AI circuits' — an agreed reference computation whose circuit-level properties can be verified by any interpretability tool, enabling cross-tool, cross-lab calibration. The TMS analog makes the BIPM-analog requirement for DC#3 concrete.","category":"insight","confidence":0.85,"created":"2026-05-08T12:08:55+00:00"}
